# Project Kennel — essential /etc subtrees catalogue (§7.4, W14)
#
# THE DEFAULT (vendor) LAYER. Installed to /usr/lib/kennel/etc-binds.catalog by the package;
# this file *is* the default set — there is no compiled-in list. kenneld binds each of these
# host /etc subtrees READ-ONLY into every constructed view (the package-managed distro content
# a confined workload needs for TLS and dynamic linking — never host-specific secrets, which
# the synthetic /etc covers separately).
#
# Composed up an ADDITIVE cascade — VENDOR + SYSTEM only:
#
#     effective set = /usr/lib/kennel/etc-binds.catalog   (this file — package default)
#                   ∪ /etc/kennel/etc-binds.catalog        (system / admin)
#
# There is NO per-user layer: widening this binds host paths into kennels (a capability), so it
# is integrity-sensitive — like the trust store, it is vendor+system only. A higher layer ADDS
# a subtree, or PRUNES one a lower layer set with a leading `-`. `#` starts a comment.
#
# A subtree appears in a kennel only if it is *also* granted via the policy's `fs.read` (the bind
# exposes it; Landlock still gates the read). Only existing paths are bound (cross-distro).

# --- CA-certificate bundles (TLS) --------------------------------------------------------
/etc/ssl/certs        # Debian/Ubuntu/Arch CA bundle + hash symlinks
/etc/ca-certificates  # Debian CA store
/etc/pki              # Red Hat/Fedora CA store + crypto policies

# --- dynamic-linker configuration --------------------------------------------------------
/etc/ld.so.conf
/etc/ld.so.conf.d
/etc/ld.so.cache      # references /usr,/lib (bound at the same paths)

# --- update-alternatives symlink farm ----------------------------------------------------
# /usr/bin/<tool> -> /etc/alternatives/<tool> -> real binary (awk->gawk, vi, editor, java, …).
# Without it the symlink dangles in the view and the tool is "command not found". Symlinks only
# (no secrets); the targets live under /usr (bound).
/etc/alternatives

# --- fontconfig ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Read-only distro font configuration: the confined GUI stack (the gui-desktop and
# gui-session-runtime fragments) resolves fonts through it. Host-generic content.
/etc/fonts
